<section xml:id="section-activity-clo8">
  <title>Activity for CLO-8</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-clo8-review">
    <title>Conceptual Review</title>
    <p>
      You can test your learning from the video (and your own
      background knowledge) with the following review questions.
      Conceptual questions on quizes may be taken from these review
      questions. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a limit?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A limit is a determine of the behaviour of a funciton when
          it approaches some value. A limit exists if a function gets
          closer and closer to some output as the input approaches
          some fixed point. If the function doe not have this
          <sq>closer and closer</sq> behaviour, the limit does not
          exist. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What does <m>\infty</m> mean, in the context of limits. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          In limits, the symbol <sq><m>\infty</m></sq> means
          <sq>getting larger and larger without bound</sq>. It is a
          symbol for a process, not a value. It means that something
          (an input, a sequence, a function) is eventually going to
          exceed any finite number as it goes through some process. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is is important to think of a limit as a process?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          It is important to think of a limit as a process because a
          limit is a process. To evaluate a function at a point is
          just to point that point into a function. It's one
          evaluation. But a limit is many, many evaluations, analyzing
          the behaviour as the input gets closer and closer to some
          fixed value. The <sq>getting closer and closer</sq> can only
          be seen as a process, not a single destination. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What do the terms <sq>converge</sq> and <sq>diverge</sq>
          mean?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          For limits, <sq>converge</sq> means that the limit exists,
          that the function does, indeed, get closer and closer to
          some finite output. In contrast, <sq>diverge</sq> means that
          the limit fails for one of many possible reasons. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a vertical asymptote?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          A vertical asymptote is a vertical line that the graph of a
          function approaches. It exists when a function has an
          inifnite limit while approaching a finite value. It
          represents the function growth very very quickly, without
          bound, in a finite amount of input space. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a one-sided limit?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          When I say <sq>closer and closer</sq>, I don't implicitly
          specify whether the nubmers are above or below the target. A
          one-sided limit makes that specification. A limit from
          below, written with a superscript negative, means that the
          nubmers getting closer and closer must be less than the
          target. A limit from above, written with a superscript
          positive, means that the numbers getting closer and closer
          must be greater than the target. 
        </p>
        <p>
          An general limit converges if and only if both of its
          one-sided versions converge. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is the three-step process to try to calculate a limit. 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First, I try to evaluate. If the limit point is actually in
          the domain of the function, then I can argue that the limit
          just approaches the function value, which is found by just
          evaluating the function.
        </p>
        <p>
          Second, I try to use a logical analysis of the pieces. This
          is most commonly done in fractions. If I can figure out
          what behaviour the numerator and denomninator have, I might
          be able to make a reasonable judgement, just on logic, about
          the behaviour of the fraction. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Third, I rely on a whole host of algebraic tools to
          manipulate the limit. Limits that don't allow the first two
          technique can not be determined direction. I need to do
          something (simplify, factor, cancel, use identities, etc) to
          change the limit to try to put it into a form where I can
          use one of the two previous techniques. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is an indeterminate form? What are the two types that
          have been introduced so far in this course? 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          An indeterminate form is a limit that requires the third
          step of the three-step process. It can't be evaluated and
          can't be determined meerly by analyzing the pieces. Hence
          <sq>indeterminate</sq>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          The two types we have covered are types <m>\frac{0}{0}</m>
          and type <m>\frac{\infty}{\infty}</m>. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What are the limit rules or the limit laws?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          These are identities for limits. Holistically, they say that
          limit cooperate with mathematical operations (addition,
          subtraction, multiplication, division, exponents) as long as
          the individual limit exist. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Why shouldn't you divide by zero?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          There are many reasons. For this course, division by zero
          often happens when trying to evaluate limits. This is out of
          step with the definition of a limit, which is a process. You
          are never actually evaluating exactly at the point; instead
          you as asking for the process approaching a point.
          Therefore, when a denominator approaches zero and the limit
          approaches infinity, you need to keep this process in mind.
          Just trying to divide by zero destroys any idea of process. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-finite-limits">
    <title>Calculation Questions: Finite Limits</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 3} 4x^2 -5 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          There are no domain restrictions here; this limit can be
          directly evaluated. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 3} 4x^2 -5 = 4(3)^2 - 5 = 31
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 3} \frac{1}{x-3}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I cannot directly evaluate, since that would lead to
          division by zero. However, I can logically analyze this
          limit. The numerator is fixed and the denominator is getting
          very small. Division by smaller and smaller numbers leads to
          larger and larger numbers. I conclude the limit must be
          infinite.The denominator can be negative or positive, so we
          write 
         <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 3} \frac{1}{x-3} = \pm \infty
          </md>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 2} \frac{x^2 - 5x + 6}{x^2 - 7x + 10} 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The numerator and denominator both approach zero. This is an
          indeterminate form of type <m>\frac{0}{0}</m>. I need to do
          some manipulations to deal with it. Both terms are
          quadratic, so I will try to factor them to simplify the
          limit. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{x \rightarrow 2} \frac{x^2 - 5x + 6}{x^2 - 7x + 10} 
              \amp = \lim_{x \rightarrow 2} \frac{(x-2)(x-3)}{(x-2)(x-5)} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{x \rightarrow 2} \frac{x-3}{x-5}
            </mrow>
          </md>
          After cancelling the <m>(x-2)</m> term, this is now a limit
          that can be directly evaluated.
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 2} \frac{x-3}{x-5} = \frac{2-3}{2-5} =
            \frac{-1}{-3} = \frac{1}{3} 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
         Calculate the limit. 
         <md>
           \lim_{x \rightarrow -3} \frac{x+3}{x^3+27} 
         </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Both the numerator and denominator approach zero, so this is
          an indeterminate form of type <m>\frac{0}{0}</m>. I can't
          do anything to the numerator, but I can factor the
          denominator to try to simplify the limit. The denominator
          factors using the special pattern for sums of cubes. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow -3} \frac{x+3}{x^3+27} =
            \lim_{x \rightarrow -3} \frac{(x+3)}{(x+3)(x^2-3x+9)} 
            = \lim_{x \rightarrow -3} \frac{1}{x^2-3x+9} 
          </md>
          This is a limit I can now directly evaluate.
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow -3} \frac{1}{x^2-3x+9} =
            \frac{1}{(-3)^2 - 3(-3) + 9} = \frac{1}{27} 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{x^4+3x^3-8x^2}{x^4 + 6x^3 +
            10x^2} 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Both numerator and denominator approach zero, so this is an
          indeterminate form of type <m>\frac{0}{0}</m>. I can factor
          <m>x^2</m> out of both numerator and denominator to simplify
          the limit. After that factoring, I can direclty evaluate. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{x^4+3x^3-8x^2}{x^4 + 6x^3 +
              10x^2} \amp = \lim_{x \rightarrow 0}
              \frac{x^2(x^2+3x-8)}{x^2(x^2+6x+10} 
            </mrow>
            <mrow> 
              \amp = \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{x^2+3x-8}{x^2+6x+10}
              = \frac{-8}{10} = \frac{-4}{5} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow \frac{1}{2}} \frac{4x^2 + 4x - 3}{8x^2 -
            2x -1}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Both numerator and denominator approach 0, so this is a
          limit of indeterminate form <m>\frac{0}{0}</m>. Both terms
          are quadratics, so I will try to factor the quadratic to
          simplify the limit. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \lim_{x \rightarrow \frac{1}{2}} \frac{4x^2 + 4x - 3}{8x^2 -
              2x -1} \amp = \lim_{x \rightarrow \frac{1}{2}}
             \frac{(2x-1)(2x+3)}{(2x-1)(4x+1)}
            </mrow>
            <mrow>
              \amp = \lim_{x \rightarrow \frac{1}{2}}
              \frac{2x+3}{4x+1}
            </mrow>
          </md>
          This is a limit I can now directly evaluate. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow \frac{1}{2}} \frac{2x+3}{4x+1}
            = \frac{1+3}{2+1} = \frac{4}{3} 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\sin^2 x}{x} 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This limit includes <m>x</m> and <m>\sin x</m>. I will 
          use the known limit for the ratio of these two
          functions. I need to manipulate this limit to isolate the known
          limit, using the rules for limits and multiplication.
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\sin^2 x}{x} = \lim_{x
            \rightarrow 0} \frac{\sin x}{x} \lim_{x \rightarrow 0}
            \sin x
          </md>
          Then the first part of this is the known limit, which
          evaluates to 1. The second part can be directly evaluated to
          0. The product of 1 and 0 is 0, so the limit is 0. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} x \cot x 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This involves trigonometry and <m>x</m>, so I will try to
          isolate the ration of <m>x</m> and <m>\sin x</m>. To do that
          I have to write cotagents in terms of sine and cosine. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} x \cot x = \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} x
            \frac{\cos x}{\sin x}
          </md>
          Then I manipulate the limit to isolate the known ratio of
          <m>x</m> amd <m>sin x</m>.
          <md>
            = \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{x}{\sin x} \cos x = \lim_{x
            \rightarrow 0} \frac{x}{\sin x} \lim_{x \rightarrow 0}
            \cos x
          </md>
          Now there are two limits, each of which evaluate to 1, so
          the original limit is also 1. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-vertical-asymptotes">
    <title>Vertical Asymptotes</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the vertical asymptotes of the the function
          <md>
            f(x) = \frac{1}{x^2-4x+3} 
          </md>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To find vertical asymptotes of a rational function, I look
          for the points on the edge of the domain and take the limits
          approaching those points. Here, domain is all real number
          except <m>x=3</m> and <m>x=1</m>. Those two numbers are the
          roots of the denominator. To determine whether there are
          vertical asymptotes at the undefined points, I need to
          take the limits approaching them. I have two limits to
          consider.
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 1} \frac{1}{x^2-4x+3} \text{ and }
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 3} \frac{1}{x^2-4x+3} 
          </md>
          Both of these limits are limits where the numerator is fixed
          and the denominator approaches 0. In these cases, dividing by
          very small numbers produced very large numbers, so the
          limits are both <m>\pm \infty</m>. Since the limits are
          infinite, I conclucde that the lines <m>x=1</m> and
          <m>x=3</m> are both vertical asymptotes. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the vertical asymptotes of the the function
          <md>
            f(x) = \frac{x-3}{x^2 + x - 12} 
          </md>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          To find vertical asymptotes of a rational function, I look
          for the points on the edge of the domain and take the limits
          approaching those points. Here, domain is all real number
          except <m>x=3</m> and <m>x=-4</m>. Those two numbers are the
          roots of the denominator. To determine whether there are
          vertical asymptotes at the undefined points, I need to
          take the limits approaching them. I have two limits to
          consider.
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 3} \frac{x-3}{(x-3)(x+4)} \text{ and }
            \lim_{x \rightarrow -4} \frac{x-3}{(x-3)(x+4)}
          </md>
          In the first limit, the <m>(x-3)</m> terms cancel out and
          the limit can be directly evaluted to <m>\frac{1}{7}</m>.
          Since this limit if not infinite, this is not a vertical
          asymptote.  In the second limit, the numerator is fixed
          and the denominator approaches 0. In this case, dividing by
          very small numbers produced very large numbers, so the
          limit is <m>\pm \infty</m>. Since the limit is 
          infinite, I conclucde that the line <m>x=-4</m> is
          is a vertical asymptote. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the vertical asymptotes of the the function
          <md>
            f(x) = \ln (x-4)
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Unlike the previous questions, this is more about
          familiarity with common functions and shifts in the plane.
          I know that the logarithm has an asymptote at <m>x=0</m>.
          Replacing <m>x</m> by <m>(x-4)</m> is a shift of 4 units in
          the positive direction, so this function has a vertical
          asymptote at <m>x=4</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the vertical asymptotes of the the function
          <md>
            f(x) = \tan (3x)
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This is also about familiarity with known functions. I
          know the tangent function has asymptotes at every odd
          multiple of <m>\frac{\pi}{2}</m>. In this function, I
          multiply by 3 inside the tangent function. This
          multiplication moves the asymptotes closer together. There
          are now asymptotes at every odd multiple of <m>
          \frac{\pi}{6}</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-finite-limits-extra-practice">
    <title>Extra Practice for Finite Limits</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 4} \sin (\pi x) - \frac{x}{3} 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This limit can be directly evaluated. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 4} \sin (\pi x) - \frac{x}{3} = \sin
            (\pi 4) - \frac{4}{3} = \frac{-4}{3} 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 4} \frac{1}{x^2 - 8x + 16} 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The numerator is fixed and the denominator approaches zero.
          A fixed number divided by a smaller and smaller number
          produces a larger and larger number, so this limit diverges
          to infinity. The denominator factors as <m>(x-4)^2</m>; it
          is a square, so it is always positive. Therefore, the limit
          diverges specifically to positive infinity. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 4} \frac{1}{x^2 - 8x + 16} = \infty 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 1^+} \sqrt{\frac{x-1}{x^2-1}}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          First, I can take the limit inside the square root. (This is
          an application of the limit laws with exponents, since the
          square root is the same as the exponent <m>\frac{1}{2}</m>.)
          <md>
            \sqrt{ \lim_{x \rightarrow 1^+} \frac{x-1}{x^2-1}}
          </md>
          Both numerator and denominator approach zero, so this is an
          indeterminate form of type <m>\frac{0}{0}</m>. I can factor
          the denominator and cancel off a term to simplify. Then I
          can directly evaluate. 
          <md>
            <mrow>
              \sqrt{ \lim_{x \rightarrow 1^+} \frac{x-1}{x^2-1}} \amp 
              = \sqrt{ \lim_{x \rightarrow 1^+}
              \frac{(x-1)}{(x-1)(x+1)}}
            </mrow>
            <mrow> 
              \amp = \sqrt{ \lim_{x \rightarrow 1^+}
              \frac{1}{x+1} } = \sqrt{\frac{1}{2}} = \frac{1}{\sqrt{2}} 
            </mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\frac{1}{x} -
            \frac{1}{x^2}}{x}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I can't even evaluate the pieces here, since there is
          division by zero in both of the fractions in the numerator.
          However, I can try to use common denominator and
          simplification of the nested fraction to put this is a more
          reasonable form. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\frac{1}{x} -
            \frac{1}{x^2}}{x} = \lim_{x \rightarrow 0}
            \frac{\frac{x-1}{x^2}}{x} = \lim_{x \rightarrow 0}
            \frac{x-1}{x^3} 
          </md>
          Then I can analyze the pieces. The numerator approaches
          <m>-1</m>. The denominator approach <m>0</m>. Something
          close to <m>-1</m> divided by smaller and smaller numbers
          produces larger and larger numbers. Therefore, I conclude
          that the limit diverges to infintiy. It could be positive or
          negative, since the denominator involves both very small
          positive and negative values approaching zero. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\frac{1}{x} -
            \frac{1}{x^2}}{x} = \pm \infty 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\cos^2 x}{x^2}
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The numerator approaches <m>1</m> and the denominator
          approach <m>0</m>. Dividing by smaller and smaller numbers
          produces larger and larger numbers, so this limit must
          diverge to inifnity. The numerator is postiive and the
          denominator, since it is a square, is also positive, so I
          know, specifically, that this diverges to positive infinity. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\cos^2 x}{x^2} = \infty 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Calculate the limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\tan^2 x}{x^2} 
          </md>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          This involves trigonometry and <m>x</m>, so I will try to
          use the know limit that relates <m>x</m> and <m>\sin x</m>.
          To do that, I'll write tangents as the ration of sine over
          cosine. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\tan^2 x}{x^2} = 
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\sin^2 x}{(\cos^2 x) x^2} = 
          </md>
          Now I can use the limit laws to break this up into pieces,
          to try to isolate the known limit. 
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\sin^2 x}{(\cos^2 x) x^2} = 
            \left( \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{1}{\cos^2 x} \right) 
            \left( \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\sin x}{x} \right) 
            \left( \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\sin x}{x} \right) 
          </md>
          Now I have isolated three limits that I know how to
          calculate. The limit with the cosine can be directly
          evaluated. The other two are both the known limit that
          evalutes to <m>1</m>.
          <md>
            \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\sin^2 x}{(\cos^2 x) x^2} = 
            \left( \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{1}{\cos^2 x} \right) 
            \left( \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\sin x}{x} \right) 
            \left( \lim_{x \rightarrow 0} \frac{\sin x}{x} \right) = 1
            \cdot 1 \cdot 1 = 1 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
</section>
